column3:
These tables include information on new prevention and relief duties owed. Prevention duties include any activities aimed at preventing a household threatened with homelessness within 56 days from becoming homeless. Relief duties are owed to households that are already homeless and require help to secure settled accommodation.

They are not comparable with the homelessness decisions or prevention/relief activity reported prior to May 2018. This is because amendments to legislation, as introduced by the 2017 HRA, have introduced new duties that mean more people will be eligible for assistance out of homelessness from local authorities. 

The national and regional totals in this data include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 5 local authorities failed to provide accurate assessments data in January to March 2023, estimated to comprise 1.32% of total assessments in England.

The national and regional totals in this data include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 6 local authorities failed to provide accurate duty end data in January to March 2023, estimated to comprise 3.28% of prevention outcomes and 4.40% of relief outcomes in England.

Main duty describes the duty a local authority has towards an applicant who is unintentionally homeless, eligible for assistance and has priority need. This definition has not been changed by the 2017 HRA. However, these households are now only owed a main duty if they did not secure accommodation in the prevention or relief stage.

The national and regional totals in this data include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 6 local authorities failed to provide accurate decisions data in January to March 2023, estimated to comprise 1.39% of total decisions in England. Moreover, 6 local authorities failed to provide accurate main duty end data, estimated to comprise 1.86% of main duty outcomes.

Unlike other data in this pack, temporary accommodation (TA) is a snapshot at the end of the quarter. It is not a cumulative total of all placements across a quarter. 

Households in temporary accommodation refer to households living in accommodation secured by a local housing authority under their statutory homelessness functions. The majority of households in temporary accommodation have been placed under the main homelessness duty to secure suitable accommodation until the duty ends. 

England and regional TA totals include imputed estimates for missing values based on previous submissions. 20 local authorities failed to provide accurate temporary accommodation figures for 31 March 2023, estimated to comprise 23.39% of total households in TA.
These tables are now only published as part of the expanded annual release at end of financial year. The latest published figures can be found in the Annual 2021-22 Detailed LA-level tables.

Data in each new release is provisional and subject to revision in future quarters. Local authorities may add new cases late or revise previous data submissions where mistakes have been spotted. 
Where revisions to earlier quarters are made, these will be incorporated into the dataset at the end of the financial year.
More information on data quality and limitations can be found in the written statistical release and technical notes:

20 authorities (as listed in TA1) did not provide accurate TA figures this quarter, and their estimated totals are categorised under 'Duty not classifiable'. 
An additional 8 local authorities identified inaccuracies in their TA duties data - these authorities have been suppressed but are included in the national and regional totals.
Includes households that were owed a main duty (S193(2)), refused to cooperate (S193C(4)), or were owed a reapplication duty (S195A(1)).
Accommodation provided under interim accommodation duties and powers: S188(1), S188(3), S190(2), S199A(2), S200(1).

Households accommodated under the Housing Act (HA) 1996 S189B power as a reasonable step towards relieving their homelessness. Placements under a S189B power have been made during the Covid-19 pandemic for rough sleepers or those at risk of rough sleeping who are eligible for assistance but not owed a S188 interim duty.  This does not reflect all rough sleepers in emergency accommodation because of missing data (particularly among London boroughs), and because others will have been accommodated under the S188 duty or outside of HA1996 assistance.
Households in TA whose duty had ended without further action, or were not found to be owed a duty following an assessment or main duty decision.

Where duty information was not provided by the local authority, including TA returns that have been imputed. Households living in temporary accommodation longest have been part of a programme to transfer cases from old systems onto H-CLIC. In some circumstances the main duty decisions were made some time ago and were not included in the data transfer. London boroughs are affected most by this issue where a significant proportion of  unclassified data is expected to be for households accommodated under S193.
